## 2. Design, Architecture & Implementation (DAI)

| Aspect | Pi (Shitty Coding Agent) | Claude (Claude Code) |
|--------|--------------------------|----------------------|
| **Core concept** | *Minimal terminal harness* that *adapts to your workflow* rather than forcing a workflow on you. | *Interactive chat‑based CLI* that works like the web Claude UI but in the terminal. |
| **Extensibility** | • **Extensions** – plug‑in code that can replace the editor, add widgets, or change the UI.<br>• **Skills** – reusable, skill‑based prompt snippets that can be triggered with `/skill:name`. <br>• **Prompt templates** – reusable prompt blocks. <br>• **Themes** – change colours, status bars, etc. <br>• **Pi‑packages** – npm‑style bundles that ship extensions, skills, etc. | • Built‑in **tools** (read, write, edit, bash, grep, etc.). <br>• Limited plugin system (MCP servers, “remote‑control” mode). <br>• No official “extension” API – you can fork the source but the binary is monolithic. |
| **Modes** | 1️⃣ Interactive (TUI)  <br>2️⃣ Print / JSON (pipe‑friendly) <br>3️⃣ RPC (for process‑to‑process integration) <br>4️⃣ SDK (for embedding in your own app) | 1️⃣ Interactive (chat) <br>2️⃣ Print / JSON (pipe‑friendly) <br>3️⃣ Remote‑control / MCP (for IDE integration) |
| **Tool handling** | The **Agent** is a thin wrapper around the Anthropic/OpenAI SDK. It receives *tool calls* from the model and dispatches them to the built‑in or custom tools. Tool names are canonicalised (`Read`, `Write`, `Edit`, …) and can be overridden by the user via `--allowed-tools`. | Same concept – the CLI parses the model’s `tool_use` blocks, normalises the names, and invokes the corresponding JavaScript function. Tool names are hard‑coded in the CLI source (`Read`, `Write`, `Edit`, `Bash`, …). |
| **Configuration** | JSON files in `~/.pi/agent/` (settings, skills, extensions, etc.).  Settings are merged from *global*, *project*, *user* scopes. | Configuration lives in `~/.claude/` (settings, plugins, MCP config).  The CLI reads a JSON file for provider credentials and has a small set of CLI flags for things like `--model`, `--thinking`, `--allowed-tools`. |
| **Provider support** | Built‑in for Anthropic, OpenAI, GitHub Copilot, Google Gemini, Vertex, Bedrock, etc.  The `@mariozechner/pi-ai` package supplies a *ModelRegistry* that knows how to talk to each provider and can inject custom headers (e.g. for Copilot or OAuth). | Primarily Anthropic (via the `@anthropic-ai/sdk`).  A few experimental providers can be added via MCP servers, but the core CLI only talks to Anthropic. |
| **Implementation language** | TypeScript → compiled to JavaScript (Node 18+).  The core agent (`@mariozechner/pi-agent-core`) is a pure‑logic library, while the CLI (`@mariozechner/pi-coding-agent`) wires it up with UI, file I/O, and the SDK. | TypeScript → compiled to JavaScript and bundled into a single binary (`claude`).  The CLI is essentially the same codebase that ships in the `claude-code` npm package, but compiled to a self‑contained executable. |
| **State/session handling** | `SessionManager` stores the entire conversation in a `.pi/session.json` file.  Branching, compaction, and resumption are all built‑in.  Sessions are *light‑weight* and can be exported as HTML. | The CLI keeps a *single* session in memory (unless `--print` is used).  The user can `--continue` or `--resume` to jump into an older session, but the CLI does not expose a branching / compaction system out of the box. |
| **UI** | Rich TUI: editor, message pane, status bar, command palette, hot‑key help, etc.  All of this is implemented with Node’s `readline` and `ansi` escape codes. | Very simple CLI: a single prompt line, model responses streamed to stdout, and the ability to run Bash commands with `!cmd`.  No “editor” widget. |
| **SDK** | `createAgentSession` returns an `AgentSession` that you can use programmatically: set tools, stream messages, access the `Agent` instance, etc.  It is fully documented in `@mariozechner/pi-coding-agent/dist/core/sdk.js`. | The CLI itself uses the *Anthropic Node SDK* (`@anthropic-ai/sdk`).  The SDK is exposed as a dependency in `claude-code` and can be imported directly in your own TypeScript/Node app.  The CLI does **not** expose a separate SDK – it just wraps the SDK in a command line interface. |

